Are we?<br>
There's no doubt in my mind that entertainment has always been consistent, only evolving in the forms it takes. Theatre, Sport, Radio, Television, Comuter games..<br>
As society changes, so does the face of entertainment. But the frequency and involvment of entertainment in everyday life never changes, it merely.. evolves.<br>
I hold an extreme opinion on this subject, as coming from a home, family, and prety much an area/society/town that doesn't see much of the online world, it makes it ever so hard for me to spend the time I wish playing EverQuest. And I feel as if I'm prety safe in suggesting that frequent players of EverQuest in our community also face the scrutiny of being told that we just play too much Computer Games.<br>
So let me lay my cards on the table.<br>
History: I've always been a social person, going out all through secondary school (highschool), college and university, involved in activities, belonging to healthy relationships and growing up in a strong family that appreciate the usual social aspects of life, such as interaction, community actitivies etc. <br>
And then one hot, summers day (sounds good, I don't actually have any evidence to suggest it was), I stumble upon EverQuest in my local Electronic Botique store. I've never been too fussed on the internet, although my family did have an internet able computer which I had ocassionaly used to go on chat rooms and to get the hang of word documents and such.<br>
So I load it up, and.. love it. Being, well younger than I am now and a bit more responsibility-free, my friends and family never took much notice when I'd start spending several evenings a week playing it, for long periods.<br>
It became something I really enjoyed, a form of entertainment, of relief from college work, a different form of interaction after an extremely nasty relationship, and just a basic chance to relax, kick back, and have a laugh.<br>
EverQuest has become something I do the most. It's become an activity I do practically every single day. I'm not a house wife, jumping on during the day, an unemployed bachelor, a happily married partner - playing extensively with my better half, I'm just your average, run of the mill, three nippled young citizen. I have no excuse to play the game from boredom or pressure, from disability or disfunction. I just like it.<br>
Now, let's take on an outsiders perspective. A perspective of those who do not play EverQuest, do not play online games. Are not concerned with the internet, even. <br>
They don't understand that it is a form of entertainment. They don't see it as we do, as a chance to meet new people, to have real fun, with other real people. They can't see how it can gain attention for hours a day, days a week, weeks a month.. years even. They cannot percieve why you would become irritable when asked to stop playing, to come offline, or when you would put off real life events for it.<br>
Dare we explain that eventually finding a group, only to loose it to the reality of life and responsibility is an annoying thing? That when you're the main crowd controller and the washing up has to wait? That real people depend on you? That it may be 'just' a game and not real life, but it is also a real consumer of real people's time and patience? Dare we, incase we face the ridicule of 'social life'?<br>
When being scrutinized by the outsider, you'll often hear such words as:<br>
Fresh air; day light; exercise; friends; life; wasting. These words will serve as a form of ideaology, as pressure to convince you that the air in the room performs its job worse than the air of the outside world, where it is fresh and somehow is better for you. <br>
Let me shed some light so you can understand my frustration with you, Outsider_01. <br>
You play golf. Let's say you play 18 holes one day, with some collegues or friends. You're hitting the 9th hole, got a few pars and possibly a birdie or two under your sleeve, but all of a sudden.. you have to stop and do something else. Annoyed? Tough shit.. you can't play golf for hours at a time! Get a grip! It's just a form of entertainment! And no, I don't give a flying fuck if it's out in the sun or not, where the air happens to be 'fresher'.<br>
Do people who watch Television for an equal amount of time you play EverQuest hold any substatial ground when grilling you on playing EverQuest for the entire evening?<br>
Perhaps the reason why some people percieve playing EverQuest for hours at a time as crazy, is because they do not realise that it is merely another form of Entertainment, something the world is not familiar enough with. <br>
I'm going to stop here, as my post is prety 'all over the place' and I don't have any actual sort of structured argument going on here. But please let me know what you think. Are the people that play EverQuest like a, god forbid, hobby.. addicted? Are they sad? Not normal? Are the EverQuest community rightfully open to scrutiny because it's not healthy, not the norm?<br>
Or am I right in suggesting that there is nothing wrong with playing something a lot, because you like it. That you can justifiably spend all evening on a computer game - not having to tell people that you do it because it's something you like to do, instead of sport or 'clubbing'.<br>
