Tank_001 has been slain by Haloface.<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/udrakzsoulsnacks.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Drakz Soulsnacks</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Regular Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/8/02 3:30:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=787.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.cross-x.com/UBB/avatars/death2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: *yawns* I present the ever-repeated debate..[Long]</span><hr size=1> Everquest is a psychological trap. Not that thats a bad thing, but honestly, thats exactly what it is.<br>
<br>
Are we obsessed? Id say so, yes. Is it our fault? Well, not entirely.<br>
<br>
Think back to every game you've played.<br>
<br>
I'll start with one of the first I played (because I cant remember the names of some of the atari ones off my head)<br>
<br>
Lets take Super Mario Bro. for instance - Old school, Nintendo.<br>
<br>
You could sit down, play it, beat it, and go back to watching TV. well, if you were an uber gamer at the time.<br>
<br>
How have games as a whole evolved from that time? There are 2 major differences in Mario Bro. and EQ.<br>
<br>
1) Multiple Real Life players living in a semi-real world environment.<br>
   EQ is a world of people, with similar interests - there are many sub-traits to this, some being<br>
a) Most folks played D&amp;D at some point in there life and/or are interested in Fantasy-based storylines and the interaction with such themes.<br>
b)Guilds become families, friends become family. Some of the most intuitive and funny people ive ever known live in EQ. Sure, I can call them, or email them - or even visit them every once in awhile - but EQ provides a meeting place for your neo-family, giving a common ground for both entertainment and friendly chatting.<br>
<br>
Now - the other factor that seperates EQ from the majority of other games.<br>
2) Complication.<br>
In almost every game, there lies one target, one boss, one main plot with one main goal.  Lets apply this scenario to life. Imagine you wake up one day, and you have to go off to Bumblefuck, USA and kill Joe Shmoe and steal his left handed smoke shifter.<br>
<br>
So you start by killing some yard trash, you get enough lunch money from beating up little kids, you go buy a baseball bat, and you beat Joe Shmoe like a red-headed step child, retrieve the smoke shifter, and w00t! Its done. You're life's destiny accomplished.<br>
<br>
So what now? Well, Joe's dead, the world is safe. So what the hell do you do with your life? You live happily ever after - doing yard work while the Mrs's goes shopping.<br>
<br>
So how did EQ get away from that? They made it real life. You dont have one goal in EQ, you have a ton of goals. there will always be something you havent done - a road you will never travel. theres simply too many things to accomplish in one sitting. You die and lose exp...you scream - but what if you never lost exp? The first couple of times you died, you'd jump for joy. But eventually, all you would worry about is losing your corpse, and you'd go on suicide runs everywhere.<br>
<br>
Mario Bros wasnt complicated.  Waste king koopa, its time for a coke and a smile.<br>
<br>
EQ? There are no winners. And, despite uber gear, uber players, and uber everything else - Everyone has the freedom to customize their lives, and EVERYONE can achieve something better than the best Equipped, best played character in the game - whoever that may be.<br>
<br>
So are we addicted? Yes, and rightfully so. The next time Outsider_01 pisses you off, just say &quot;/rude %t&quot; and see what he says.<br>
<br>
Now, if you'll excuse me, Im going to go pop some valiums.<br>
