<br>
It's no accident so many people play the game frantically for a year or a few, and then leave a hateful farewell-message stating that one have to be a total loser to play this worthless game. Of course those people are wrong, the statements are too silly to even consider since they have played so long themselves. Yet, those statements should not be disregarded. While they are not true, they are not lies either. They are outcries of emotional pain, not rational statements.<br>
<br>
I think the problem with MMORPG:s are twofold.<br>
The addictiveness and the alienation from the outside world.<br>
<br>
As have been mentioned, the game is kinda addictive in itself, and it gets much much worse by the facts that you can not pause and that you are letting down real people, real friends if you don't do your part. The game also offers a gig social enviorment in a world where people live stressful lives and RL friends often have higher priorities then you. Work, school, spouses, all that. All in all, the game make you dependent on it and make you lose some of your control of your own life. This lead to the same combination of love and hate that are often found in RL families.<br>
<br>
Secondly, once a huge time of your time is dedicated to the game and to your real friends in the game, it alienate you from your non-EQ friends and aquaintenses.<br>
<br>
First, it takes a lot of your time in ways that are partly out of your control, and thus your other friends find you unaviable in many ways. My friends really hated when they called and I was just mumbling to them while attending my group or raid, and I later got to feel the same kind of resentment myself. (Combined with the horrifying revelation &quot;oh no, I was like that&quot;.)<br>
<br>
Second, like Halo said, the sum of the entertainment is constant. Play 20 hours of EverQuest compared to 20 hours of giving 10 movies or single player games 2 hours each.<br>
<br>
Now first put this into the perspective of &quot;what does this, in itself, give me?&quot;. We will all respond that EverQuest gives more. It's interactive and it's social, while the alternatives are solitary and basically non-interactive. Single player games are interactive as opposed to movies, but the interaction is stale since you are interactive with solid predefined parameters, as oppsoed to the social dynamics of the EQ player base.<br>
<br>
But now lets put this into another perspective! What does the entertainment give you to talk about with your non-EQ friends? When we think about it we will find that EACH movie and single player game will give us more to mindlessly babble about then the entire 20h EverQuest episode, unless it's the first time you tell about the game as such. The surface of EQ is kinda bleak and people who have not played themselves cannot understand the subtilities or are at least not interested in them. Many will also be un-understanding on a deeper level, finding the whole thing to be creepy and act accordingly. <br>
